  "summary": "Malicious npm package: console.log hijack exfiltrating to hardcoded Telegram bot",
  "details": "Package 11j@1.1.1 is a throwaway npm package whose main entrypoint (mod.js) replaces console.log with a function that exfiltrates every logged argument via fetch() to a hardcoded Telegram Bot API endpoint with an attacker-controlled bot token and chat_id. A sibling file m.js repeats the exact same exfiltration pattern with the identical token, confirming deliberate intent. The package also ships hardcoded Telegram bot credentials and Cloudflare Global API Key + email for account d9c4a171c4a0d0a8e6f8204ae9ba0638, plus unsolicited PATCH/GET calls to attacker-owned Firebase databases. Metadata is placeholder-tier with empty index.js, no README/author/license, and a syntax-broken alert() call — all consistent with a malware drop rather than a real library. Multiple independent block signals: console.log monkey-patch exfiltrator, hardcoded credential distribution, third-party data-relay backends, and placeholder metadata.",
